propagate_gene_ontology.r
2014-05-26 dmontaner@cipf.es
The script shows how to propagate Gene Ontology annotation using R and Bioconductor.

In this practical we will propagate the Gene Ontology annotation found in the AmiGO browser for the human gene SMN1.

Download the annotation data from the AmiGO page and save it in a file named annotation_smn1.txt. See video here.

You will also need to install the Bioconductor packages GO.db and RamiGO.

Plot the DAG structure

We will use the library

library(RamiGO)

> Loading required package: gsubfn
> Loading required package: proto
> Note: the specification for S3 class "AsIs" in package 'XMLRPC' seems equivalent to one from package 'BiocGenerics': not turning on duplicate class definitions for this class.

# help (package = RamiGO)

We can first plot the original terms. Let's set GO ID's and color

goIDs <- datos[, 2]
color <- "red"

Now we can get the pot in PNG format

pp <- getAmigoTree(goIDs = goIDs, color = color, filename = "datos/annotated_gos")

The plot should be now: get the pot in SVG format

pp <- getAmigoTree(goIDs = goIDs, color = color, filename = "datos/annotated_gos", 
    picType = "svg")

The SVM plot must be here We can also plot the directly annotated and the propagated terms using different colors

new.gos <- setdiff(gos, datos[, 2])
goIDs <- c(datos[, 2], new.gos)
color <- c(rep("red", times = length(datos[, 2])), rep("blue", times = length(new.gos)))
